{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_hedgehog_ver01/data/sn84020558/00211104570/1907121901/0235.xml":{"full_text":"THE ARIZONA REPUBLICAN, TIIURSDAY MOItXIXG, DECE3IBER 19, 1907.\nia...aaaaaaBBBBaaal'\nGet In Line\nlO Per Cent OFF\nOn All\nBUGGIES AND SURRIES\nUntil\nJan. U 1908\nEZRA W.\n124-1SO E. Wash. st.\nTHAYER\n127-133 E.. Adams st.\nfrom now on; that in his Judgment\nPresident Roosevelt'j announcement\nJust made would have a good effect.\nH said that business in the southwest\nhad been plowing down quite notiee\nal.lv In the nast few months, \"and that\nthere was only one factory he knew\nof in the country thnt had not been\ncompelled to curtail operations, namely\nthe W. J. Bryan canning factory,\nwhich had been and still was working\novertime putting up Bryan's canned\nharangues of the 18!6 and 190 brand.\nI Mr. Murphy said: \"However,\nthere is trouble ahead for W. J. B., as\nlie does not .seem to realize that the j\ncountry has been surfeited anil his\ngoods are being rejected everywhere,\njimd it may be expected that this busy\n.enierpiine nm ww iim mc\n'a receiver early in the fall, if not in\n'June. The canned goods referred to,\n'got a (Treat hoost when the adminis\ntration took them up, changing the la\njhel just a little by referring to the\ntheoretical reform vote catching dope\nithat had been added. But the people\nhave had onough and the business In\nterests of ihe country should soon be\n'ein to recover from the ptomaine ef-\n'fects from which tlipy have been suf-\ni fi ring more or less for the past few I\nars. the acute stase Having oeen\nreadied in the last ninety day.\" i\nso\nYOUR\nO\nCHRISTMAS\nShopping\nTHE KEYNOTE OF MOST OF THE CHRISTMAS GIFT GIVING\nTHIS YEAR CAN BE EXPRESSED IN ONE WORD:\n1 Usefulness Christmas Neckwear\nSmOKE\nThe\nARTICLES OF INCORPORATION\nCf the Goldmont Mining and\nCompany.\nWe the undersigned for the purpose\ni. f forming a corporation under the\nhiws of the Territory of Arizona to\ntransact the business hereinafter men\ntioned do adopt the following Articles\nof Incorporation.\nFirst. The names of the corporators\nare Homer lVnnock. Raymond 1- Hig\n;:;ns and Edmunds P. Schmidt.\nThe name of the corporation is The\nColdmont Minins and Milling company\nand the principal place of transacting\nbusiness shall be at Phoenix in said\nterritory, but the corporation proposes\nto carry on business in the United\nStates and in such other place or plac\nes as may be found necessary for the\nproper conduct of its business. The\ni ompany may have offices at such\nplaces as may be required, and a stock\ntransfer office in the state of Pennsyl\nvania or at such place wherein the\nmajority of the oflicers of the said\ncorporation reside and do its business.\nSecond. The general nature of the\nbusiness proposed to be transacted\nwill be the mining for gold, silver, cop-\nMilling Iper. precious stones and othT min\nerals and the proper preparation or\nthe same for market. The construc\ntion of roads also the building of hous\nes and trading in merchandise. For\nall of these purposes the company will\nacquire, hold, use and work mining\nrights and proiierty. and such other\nrights and property as may be neces\nsary in carrying on the business herein\nset forth or connected therewith.\nThird. The amount of the capital I\nstock of this corporation shall be Five\nMillion dollars divided into Five Mil\nlion shares of the par value of one dol\nlar each, and said capital stock shall\nbe paid up at the date of Issuance, or\nat such time as the Board of Directors\nmay designate, in money, property,\nlabor, or any other valuable right or\nthing, and the judgement of the Board\nof Directors or- managing officers as\nto the value thereof shall be conclu-\nsie. j\nFourth. The time of the commence\nment of this corporation shall be the j\nTHE PROMISED LAND\n\"Paradise of the World\"\nLos Angeles, California and the Southwest\nTake an Enjoyabie Trip Through It by Pen and Picture\nvia\nLos Angeles Times\nNew Year's Number\nITiO pages, in five magazine parts, with authentic text compiled by\nexperienced writers \"on the spot.\" profuselv illustrated with actual\nplmtof rai.lis in full pafie groups anil smaller half tones.\nLearn all about thi- rich world n itself, located In the extreme\nsouthwestern part of the L'nitcd States: its present status, advancing\ndevelopment, brilliant prosjwets. production of oranfes and oil, build\ning development and mineral wealth.\nSixteen cents, mailed anywhere after January 1, 1907. Send ad\nvance orders.\nThe TIMES-MIRROR Company\nPubs. Los Angeles Cal.\nHarrison Gray Otis, General Manager\nOUR MEATS\nMAKE THE MOUTH WATER\nWe sre busy getting out orders these days, because we serve only\nthe very best. We know that you want only good meats, so why\nwould we want to dissatisfv you'.'\nNO KICK COMING ON MEATS FROM OUR SHOP.\nIt is worth something to have meats that you enjoy at the dining\ntable.\nTRY AN ORDER FROM US.\nJ. E. STURGECN CO.\nin the office of the Auditor of Arizona\nand the termination thereof shall be\ntwenty-live years thereafter.\nFifth. The affairs of this corpora\ntion will be conducted by a Board of\nDirectors consisting of not less than\nfive persons, from whom there will be\nselected a president, vice-president,\nsecretary and treasurer, and an ex\necutive committee. The election or\nappointment of other oflicers or agents\nof the company that may be found\nnecessary in the conduct of its busi\nness wiil be provided for in the by\nlaws ofthe company.\nSixth. Flections of directors shall\nbe held annually on the first Wed\nnesday in December and an election\nof officers .hall be made at the first\nmeeting of the board of directors\nthereafter.\nSeventh. The highest amount of in\ndebtedness or liability to which this\ncorporation shall subject itself Is three\nhundred thousand dollars.\nEighth. Private iircperty of the\nmembers of this corporation shall be\nexempt from corporate debts.\nNinth. Among the owers of this\nbody cororate shall be: 1st. To have\nperpetual succession. 2nd. To sue\nand be sued by the corporate name.\ni 3rd to have a common seal and alter\nthe same at pleasure. 4th. To ren\nder the shares or interest of stock\nholders transferable and prescribe the\nmode of making such transfers, Sth.\nTo exemiit the private property of\nmembers from liability for corporate\ndebts. 6th. To make contracts, ac\nquire and transfer property possess-\nI ing the same powers in sues respect\nas private individuals now enjoy.\n7th. To establish by-laws and make\nall rules and regulations deemed ex\npedient for the management of their\naffairs, not inconsistant with the con\nstitution and laws of the I'nited States\n'and the Territory of Arizona,\nj In witness whereof we have here\nunto set our hands and seals this 31st\nday of October, one thousand nine\nhundred and seven.\nHOMER PEXXOCK (Seal)\nI RAYMOND P HK'.C.IXS (Seal)\nj KPMVXD P. SCHMIDT (Seal)\nI Witness;\nI. A. NICHOLS\nF. M. COI.E\nState of Pennsylvania.\nCity and County of Philadelphia ss\nBe it remembered that on this\nthirty-first day of October one thou-\nsand nine hundred and seven before\nme the subscriber a Notary Public\nauthorized to take acknowledgement\nand proof of deeds etc. to be used or\nrecorded personally appeared the\nabove named Homer Pcnnock. Ray-\ni iron Higgins, Edmund P. Schmidt,\npersonally known to me to be the per-\nsons whose names are subscribed to\nI the foregoing instrument and severally\nacknowledged to me that they execut\ned the tame for the uses and puroses\nand consideration therein expressed.\nj Given under my hand and official\nseal the day and year in this certificate\nfirst above written.\n(Seal) LILLIAN EVANS FRIEL.\nj Notary Public.\nMy commission expires January 21,\n1811.\no\nWESltRNER'S VIEW\nOF BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nPROSPECTIVE DIAL 1\nFOR 4 RICH MINE!\nIN HANDSOME STYLES, CHOICE AND EXCLUSIVE\nSHIRTS. GLOVES. MUFFLERS. HOSIERY, NIGHT\nMAS, BATH ROBES, UMBRELLAS, SLIPPERS, SUIT\nHAND BAGS, SHOES.\nDESIGNS.\nROBES, PAJA-\nCASES.\nProbable Sale of a Promising Proper- j\nty in the Now Famout Wenden Sec-\ntier..\nHoward C Cassidy\nof Los Angeles,\nMacaroni Co.\npresident of he Cassidy\nis in the city, a'guest of the Hotel Ad-\nims. Mr. Cassidy arrived yesterday\nfrom Wenden and has been for several\ndays past making an inspection of the\nmany fine mines and prospects In tnat\nvicinity, in company with Mr. Carr,\nsuperintendent of one of the mines.\nOne of the properties in that section\nis a partially develoied prospect own\ned bv Phil Wharton and Billy Palmer.\nMention was made of it in The Repub\nlican sometime ago when a lot of ore\nw.is brought in from the mine, the\nquality of which had the effect of\nmaking a man feel rich just to look at\nit. Ever since that lime Messrs.\nW harton and Palmer have been rated\nas millionaires, inougn oi course iney\nhave been careful not to overdraw\ntheir bank- accounts, for everybody\nknows that gold in th 'ground is no\nbetter than clearing house scrip for\ncirculation purposes.\nMr. Cassidy looked at this mine\namong others, and it was a case of\nlove at first sight. It is understood\nhe is here now to close up a oeal for\nit. but will have to wait a day or two\nfor Mr. Palmer to return from Agua\nCaliente. where he has been- with a\nparty of friends for a few days. Mr.\nWharton could turn over the mine and\ntake the million dollars he ought to get\nfor it and blow the country, but he Is\nnot that kind of a man. He refuses to\nbecome wealthy unless his friends get\ntheir share. Mr. Cassidy could not be\nfound last night to verify the story,\nbut nside from all Joking it is expect\ned that a deal will be consummated\nand the property has all the evidence\nof being a large and valuable one.\nJUST THE SORT OF GIFT\nA MAN WILL APPRECIATE.\nare\nIf you\ntake pleasure\nto have.\nwe'll\n..,V.-;rl..d to iust what to buy him fcr Christmas,\nIt I I- J\nin showing you a host of thirds o wouia ne aeuantea\nAgents for\